    <h2>Pine Script</h2>
    <p>In the first issue of Pine Lines, we learned that Pine Script is TradingView's very own built-in programming language.</p>
    <p>While only being restricted to TradingView, Pine Script remains highly versatile. As mentioned in "Welcome to Pine Lines," Pine Script's syntax is very similar to Python and Java. These similarities consist of data types, variables, functions, and more.</p>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>Programming Fundamentals</h2>
    <p>Every programming language has a designated set of rules — this is called <strong>syntax</strong>. Here are the basics to understand when programming in Pine Script and other languages.</p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Comments:</strong> notes that the programmer writes; the computer ignores these notes. In Pine Script there are single-line and multi-line comments, declared with the same syntax as a Java comment, using <code class="inline">//</code>. In Python, comments are declared with <code class="inline">#</code>.</li>
      <li><strong>Variables:</strong> a name given to a piece of information to use later.</li>
      <li><strong>Inputs:</strong> allow you to change settings from a menu rather than editing code.</li>
      <li><strong>Functions:</strong> similar to Algebra, a function in code takes an input and returns an output.</li>
      <li><strong>Data types:</strong> the values a programming language can understand and use — they are like labels.</li>
    </ul>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>Functions</h2>
    <p>Functions are a block of code used to perform a specific task. Rather than writing the same code multiple times, you can "define" a function and later "call" it when required.</p>
    <p>In Python, a function is defined using the <code class="inline">def</code> keyword. These functions can take inputs (also known as parameters) and return outputs.</p>

    <div class="code-label">Python — example function (Google Colab)</div>
