    </div>

    <p>In Pine Script, functions can be defined on a single line or across multiple lines. Here are a few sample functions in the Pine Editor on TradingView:</p>

    <div class="note-box">
      <strong>Please note:</strong> these functions are examples and will not be used when programming — they're here to demonstrate the syntax of an indicator in Pine Script.
    </div>

    <div class="code-label">Pine Editor — single-line &amp; multi-line functions</div>
    <div class="screenshot">
      <img src="data:image/png;base64," alt="Pine Editor showing a single-line Hello,World indicator and a multi-line averageOfTwo function">
    </div>

    <p>The single-line function defines an indicator with the name "Hello, World." There is no calculation being made, and nothing is being displayed.</p>
    <p>In the multi-line function, an indicator named <code class="inline">averageOfTwo</code> calculates the average of two numbers. First it adds them up (<code class="inline">sum = x + y</code>), then divides by two (<code class="inline">sum / 2</code>), then returns the result. The <code class="inline">plot()</code> function plots the average on the chart.</p>

    <h3>Other Types of Functions in Pine Script</h3>
    <p><strong>Built-in functions:</strong> functions provided by TradingView on the Pine Script library. These include <code class="inline">ta</code>, <code class="inline">math</code>, <code class="inline">request</code>, <code class="inline">strategy</code>, and more.</p>

    <div class="code-label">Examples of built-in functions</div>
