  <section>
    <h2>Variables in Pine Script</h2>
    <p>Think of variables like containers that store information you can later manipulate. In Pine Script, variables are important because they help keep track of values across time periods on a chart.</p>
    <p>You declare a variable by giving it a name and assigning (<code class="inline">=</code>) it a value. In Python, variables can be changed at any time and keep their values until the end of the program. In Pine Script, however, the difference is that variables recalculate on every bar of the chart — unless you use a persistent variable (<code class="inline">var</code>).</p>

    <h3>Persistent Variables (var)</h3>
    <p>Python does not require special keywords because values persist automatically:</p>
    <pre>counter = 0
counter = counter + 1</pre>

    <p>In Pine Script, you need to declare <code class="inline">var</code> to remember values across bars (time periods):</p>
    <pre><span class="keyword">var</span> counter = 0
counter := counter + 1
<span class="func">plot</span>(counter)</pre>
    <p>Without <code class="inline">var</code>, <code class="inline">counter</code> would reset back to 0 on each new bar.</p>

    <div class="note-box">
      <strong>Key takeaway:</strong> in Pine Script, variables reset every bar unless declared with <code class="inline">var</code>. In Python, variables are "normal" and persist by default.
    </div>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>Plotting / Visualization</h2>
    <p>The <code class="inline">plot()</code> function allows you to visualize data in Pine Script:</p>
    <pre><span class="func">plot</span>(series, title, color, linewidth, style)</pre>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>series</strong> — the data shown (close, open, etc.)</li>
      <li><strong>title</strong> — a label for the plot</li>
      <li><strong>color</strong> — the line color (<code class="inline">color.orange</code>, <code class="inline">color.blue</code>, etc.)</li>
      <li><strong>linewidth</strong> — thickness of the line</li>
      <li><strong>style</strong> — the style of the plot (<code class="inline">plot.style.line</code>, <code class="inline">plot.style.histogram</code>, etc.)</li>
    </ul>

